{
  "text": "Despite the competence-based approach for the design and assessment of educational programs and activities has been established as shared basis of all the educational systems in the European Union for more than 10 years, the effectiveness of this educational paradigm still lacks of solid empirical confirmation [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "78110406"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "78110406": {
      "title": "Competence-based Education and Educational Effectiveness",
      "abstract": "The chapter assesses the empirical evidence for outcomes of competence-based education which are envisaged by policy-makers, and gives some interpretations of how the topic is handled in the political processes. This is achieved by a review of the research literature as documented in bibliographical databases which cover academic publications and in more practical material. The searches were generic, and included not only specific competence-expressions, but also terms as \u2018outcomes\u2019 and \u2018learning\u2019. The staggering conclusion of this exercise is that there is hardly any evidence for the effectiveness of competence-based education despite the long period since the 1970s when the approach came up in the US. Whether this is an artefact of the operationalization of the outcomes of competence-based education or not, it seems that there is only very little attention to testing the policy-assumptions that competence-based education is a worthy educational innovation. As this is quite disturbing, it is recommended that more efforts are being made to prove (or falsify) the putative added value of competence-based education initiatives."
    }
  }
}